{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:170","names":{"en":"'Ādil Shāhī","tr":"Âdilşâhîler","ar":"al-'Ādil Shāhiyyūn"},"country":["AF","BD","IN","PK"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":1686},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"170","atlas_name_en_original":"The 'Ādil Shāhīs","parent_tribe":"Yûsuf Âdil ailesi (Türk/İranî)","ethnic_origin":"Türk veya İranî (Safevî bağlantısı iddiası)","capital":"Bîcâpûr","region_primary":"Bîcâpûr","regions_all":"Bîcâpûr; Goa (kısmen)","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Bahmânîler","successor":"Bâbürlü Evrengzîb ilhakı (1097/1686)","government_type":"Şahlık","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The 'Ādil Shāhīs were a dynasty that established one of the Deccan's most powerful sultanates centered on Bijapur, building the Gol Gumbaz. The reign of Ibrāhīm 'Ādil Shāh II represents the pinnacle of cultural and artistic patronage. They ruled for approximately 200 years until Mughal Awrangzīb's conquests.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"16.83","capital_lon":"75.71","century_start":15,"century_end":17}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:169","names":{"en":"Barīd Shāhī","tr":"Berîdşâhîler","ar":"al-Barīd Shāhiyyūn"},"country":["AF","BD","IN","PK"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"169","atlas_name_en_original":"The Barīd Shāhīs","parent_tribe":"Berîd ailesi (Türk kökenli)","ethnic_origin":"Türk/Dekkan","capital":"Bîdâr","region_primary":"Bîdâr","regions_all":"Bîdâr","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Bahmânîler","successor":"Âdilşâhî/Bâbürlü ilhakı","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Barīd Shāhīs ruled centered on Bidar as one of the Bahmanid successor sultanates. They ended with annexation by the 'Ādil Shāhīs.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"17.91","capital_lon":"77.52","century_start":15,"century_end":17}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:177","names":{"en":"Nawwāb-Viziers and Kings of Oudh (Awadh)","tr":"Avadh (Oudh) Nevvâb-Vezirleri ve Kralları","ar":"Nawwāb-Viziers of Awadh"},"country":["AF","BD","IN","PK"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":1856},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"177","atlas_name_en_original":"The Nawwāb-Viziers and Kings of Oudh (Awadh)","parent_tribe":"Sa'âdet Han ailesi (İranî)","ethnic_origin":"İranî","capital":"Fayzâbâd → Lucknow","region_primary":"Avadh (Lucknow)","regions_all":"Lucknow; Fayzâbâd; Avadh","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Bâbürlü valileri","successor":"İngiliz ilhakı (1856)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":"Şiî","narrative_en":"The Nawwābs of Awadh were a dynasty that created a wealthy Islamic cultural center with Shī'ī character centered on Lucknow. Lucknow's literary, musical, and architectural tradition took shape in this period. The British annexation in 1856 ignited one of the most violent fronts of the 1857 Great Rebellion a year later.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"26.85","capital_lon":"80.95","century_start":18,"century_end":19}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:171","names":{"en":"Nizām Shāhī","tr":"Nizâmşâhîler","ar":"al-Nizām Shāhiyyūn"},"country":["AF","BD","IN","PK"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"171","atlas_name_en_original":"The Nizām Shāhīs","parent_tribe":"Ahmed Nizâm ailesi (Brahman dönme)","ethnic_origin":"Hindistanlı Müslüman (dönme)","capital":"Ahmednagar","region_primary":"Ahmednagar","regions_all":"Ahmednagar; Dekkan","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Bahmânîler","successor":"Bâbürlü Şâhcihân ilhakı","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Nizām Shāhīs were a Bahmanid successor sultanate centered on Ahmednagar, entering history through Chand Bībī's heroic resistance against the Mughals. Ruling for approximately 145 years, they were conquered by Mughal Shāhjahān.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"19.08","capital_lon":"74.74","century_start":15,"century_end":17}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:178","names":{"en":"Nāzims of Hyderabad","tr":"Haydarâbâd Nizâmları","ar":"Nizām al-Mulk fī Haydarābād"},"country":["AF","BD","IN","PK"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":1948},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"178","atlas_name_en_original":"The Nāzims of Hyderabad","parent_tribe":"Âsafcâh ailesi (Türk kökenli)","ethnic_origin":"Türk/İranî","capital":"Haydarâbâd","region_primary":"Haydarâbâd (Dekkan)","regions_all":"Haydarâbâd; Dekkan; Golkonda","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Bâbürlü Dekkan valileri","successor":"Hindistan Cumhuriyeti ilhakı (1948 Polis Eylemi)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Nizāms of Hyderabad were a dynasty that established India's largest and wealthiest princely state by gaining independence from Mughal Deccan governorship. Maintaining independence until 1948, Hyderabad survived as a British ally and its incorporation into India was only achieved through 'Police Action.'","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"17.38","capital_lon":"78.49","century_start":18,"century_end":20}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:173","names":{"en":"Qutb Shāhī","tr":"Kutubşâhîler","ar":"al-Qutb Shāhiyyūn"},"country":["AF","BD","IN","PK"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":1687},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"173","atlas_name_en_original":"The Qutb Shāhīs","parent_tribe":"Kara Yûsuf Türkmen ailesi (Karakoyunlu bağlantısı)","ethnic_origin":"Türk (Türkmen)","capital":"Golkonda → Haydarâbâd","region_primary":"Golkonda / Haydarâbâd","regions_all":"Golkonda; Haydarâbâd; Telengana; Andhra","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Bahmânîler","successor":"Bâbürlü Evrengzîb fethi (1098/1687)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Qutb Shāhīs were a dynasty of Turkmen origin that established one of the wealthiest Deccan sultanates centered on Golconda. Golconda's diamond mines — including the Koh-i Noor — produced world-famous treasures. Founding the city of Hyderabad and building the Charminar, the Qutb Shāhīs were the architects of the Telugu-Islamic cultural synthesis.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"17.38","capital_lon":"78.49","century_start":15,"century_end":17}}
